    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Here's a neat solution:</p>\n<pre><code>String upToNCharacters = s.substring(0, Math.min(s.length(), n));\n</code></pre>\n<hr />\n<p><sup>Opinion: while this solution is &quot;neat&quot;, I think it is actually <em>less readable</em> than a solution that uses <code>if</code> / <code>else</code> in the obvious way.  If the reader hasn't seen this trick, he/she has to <em>think harder</em> to understand the code.  IMO, the code's meaning is more obvious in the <code>if</code> / <code>else</code> version.  For a cleaner / more readable solution, see <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/1583971/139985\">@paxdiablo's answer</a>.</sup></p>\n"
  }, {
